The disposition effect is a behavioral finance concept where investors tend to sell winning assets too soon (locking in gains) and hold losing assets too long (hoping for recovery). It's driven by aversion to realizing losses, per prospect theory. In markets like gold/silver, it can amplify sell-offs or prolong slumps.
